 {{flag|Togo}}\n| {{dts|1982|Dec|10}}\n| {{dts|1985|Apr|16}}\n| Ratification\n| {{dts|1994|Aug|3}}\n| {{dts|1995|Jul|28}}\n| Ratification\n|-\n| {{flag|Tonga}}\n|\n| {{dts|1995|Aug|2}}\n| Accession\n|\n| {{dts|1995|Aug|2}}\n| Accession\n|-\n| {{flag|Trinidad and Tobago}}\n| {{dts|1982|Dec|10}}\n| {{dts|1986|Apr|25}}\n| Ratification\n| {{dts|1994|Oct|10}}\n| {{dts|1995|Jul|28}}\n| Ratification\n|-\n| {{flag|Tunisia}}\n| {{dts|1982|Dec|10}}\n| {{dts|1985|Apr|24}}\n| Ratification\n| {{dts|1995|May|15}}\n| {{dts|2002|May|24}}\n| Ratification\n|-\n| {{flag|Tuvalu}}\n| {{dts|1982|Dec|10}}\n| {{dts|2002|Dec|9}}\n| Ratification\n|\n| {{dts|2002|Dec|9}}\n| Accession\n|-\n| {{flag|Uganda}} {{dagger}}\n| {{dts|1982|Dec|10}}\n| {{dts|1990|Nov|9}}\n| Ratification\n| {{dts|1994|Aug|9}}\n| {{dts|1995|Jul|28}}\n| Ratification\n|-\n| {{flag|Ukraine}}\n| {{dts|1982|Dec|10}}\n| {{dts|1999|Jul|26}}\n| Ratification\n| {{dts|1995|Feb|28}}\n| {{dts|1999|Jul|26}}\n| Ratification\n|-\n| {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n| \n| {{dts|1997|Jul|25}}\n| Accession\n| {{dts|1994|Jul|29}}\n| {{dts|1997|Jul|25}}\n| Ratification\n|-\n| {{flag|Uruguay}}\n| {{dts|1982|Dec|10}}\n| {{dts|1992|Dec|10}}\n| Ratification\n| {{dts|1994|Jul|29}}\n| {{dts|2007|Aug|7}}\n| Ratification\n|-\n| {{flag|Vanuatu}}\n| {{dts|1982|Dec|10}}\n| {{dts|1999|Aug|10}}\n| Ratification\n| {{dts|1994|Jul|29}}\n| {{dts|1999|Aug|10}}\n| Ratification\n|-\n| {{flag|Vietnam}}\n| {{dts|1982|Dec|10}}\n| {{dts|1994|Jul|25}}\n| Ratification\n|\n| {{dts|2006|Apr|27}}\n| Accession\n|-\n| {{flag|Yemen}}\n| {{dts|1982|Dec|10}}\n| {{dts|1987|Jul|21}}\n| Ratification as the [[People's Democratic Republic of Yemen]].<br>Also signed by the [[Yemen Arab Republic]] on Dec. 10 1982 <br>prior to [[Yemeni unification]].<ref name=rat/>\n|\n| {{dts|2014|Oct|13}}\n| Accession\n|-\n| {{flag|Zambia}} {{dagger}}\n| {{dts|1982|Dec|10}}\n| {{dts|1983|Mar|7}}\n| Ratification\n| {{dts|1994|Oct|13}}\n| {{dts|1995|Jul|28}}\n| Ratification\n|-\n| {{flag|Zimbabwe}} {{dagger}}\n| {{dts|1982|Dec|10}}\n| {{dts|1993|Feb|24}}\n| Ratification\n| {{dts|1994|Oct|28}}\n| {{dts|1995|Jul|28}}\n| Ratification\n|}\n\n==Signatories==\nAn additional 14 UN member states have signed the Convention but have not ratified it. One UN member state has signed the Agreement but has not ratified it.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!State<ref name=rat/><ref name=rat2/><ref name=undep/>\n! Signed<br>Convention\n!Signed<br>Agreement\n|-\n| {{flag|Afghanistan}} {{dagger}}\n| {{dts|1983|Mar|18}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Bhutan}} {{dagger}}\n| {{dts|1982|Dec|10}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Burundi}} {{dagger}}\n| {{dts|1982|Dec|10}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Cambodia}}\n| {{dts|1983|Jul|1}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Central African Republic}} {{dagger}}\n| {{dts|1984|Dec|4}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Colombia}}\n| {{dts|1982|Dec|10}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|El Salvador}}\n| {{dts|1984|Dec|5}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Ethiopia}} {{dagger}}\n| {{dts|1982|Dec|10}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Iran}}\n| {{dts|1982|Dec|10}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|North Korea}}\n| {{dts|1982|Dec|10}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Libya}}\n| {{dts|1984|Dec|3}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Liechtenstein}} {{dagger}}\n| {{dts|1984|Nov|30}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Rwanda}} {{dagger}}\n| {{dts|1982|Dec|10}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|United Arab Emirates}}\n| {{dts|1982|Dec|10}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|United States}}\n|\n| {{dts|1994|Jul|29}}\n|}\n\n==Other states==\nThere are 15 United Nations member and observer states which have neither signed nor acceded either the Convention or the Agreement:\n\n{{Col-begin}}{{Col-4}}\n* {{flag|Andorra}} {{dagger}}\n* {{flag|Eritrea}}\n* {{flag|Israel}}\n* {{flag|Kazakhstan}} {{dagger}}\n{{Col-4}}\n* {{flag|Kyrgyzstan}} {{dagger}}\n* {{flag|Peru}}\n* {{flag|San Marino}} {{dagger}}\n* {{flag|South Sudan}} {{dagger}}\n{{Col-4}}\n* {{flag|Syria}}\n* {{flag|Tajikistan}} {{dagger}}\n* {{flag|Turkey}}\n* {{flag|Turkmenistan}} {{dagger}}\n{{Col-4}}\n* {{flag|Uzbekistan}} {{dagger}}\n* {{flag|Holy See}} {{dagger}}\n* {{flag|Venezuela}}\n{{Col-end}}\n\n== United States position ==\n{{main|United States non-ratification of the UNCLOS}}\nAlthough the United States helped shape the Convention and its subsequent revisions,<ref>[http://www.history.state.gov/historicaldocuments/frus1969-76ve03/ch1 Documents on Global Issues, 1973-1976] [[Foreign Relations Series]]</ref> and though it signed the 1994 Agreement on Implementation, it has not signed the Convention as it objected to Part XI of the Convention.<ref name=rufe>[http://www.foreign.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/RufeTestimony031021.pdf Roger Rufe, President of the Ocean Conservancy. Statement before the Senate Committee on Foreign Relations, October 21, 2003]</ref><ref>V Bantz, 'La Question De I'Adhesion Par Les Etats-Unis a La Convention Des Nations Unies Sur Le Droit De La Mer' (2003) 8 Annuaire Du Droit De La Mer 9\u201354</ref>\n\nIn 1983 President [[Ronald Reagan]], through [[Presidential proclamation|Proclamation]] No. 5030, claimed a 200-mile exclusive economic zone. In December 1988 President Reagan, through Proclamation No. 5928, extended U.S. territorial waters from three nautical miles to twelve nautical miles for national security purposes. However a legal opinion from the [[United States Department of Justice|Justice Department]] questioned the President's constitutional authority to extend sovereignty as Congress has the power to make laws concerning the territory belonging to the United States under the U.S. Constitution. In any event, Congress needs to make laws defining if the extended waters, including oil and mineral rights, are under State or Federal control.<ref name=nyt-19881229>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/12/29/us/reagan-extends-territorial-waters-to-12-miles.html |title=Reagan Extends Territorial Waters to 12 Miles |author=Andrew Rosenthal |newspaper=New York Times |date=29 December 1988 |accessdate=23 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=http://ir.lawnet.fordham.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1362&context=ilj |title=U.S. Territorial Sea Extension: Jurisdiction and International Environmental Protection |author=Carol Elizabeth Remy |journal=Fordham International Law Journal |year=1992 |volume=16 |issue=4 |pages=1208\u20131252 |accessdate=23 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 July 2012, the U.S. Senate had 34 Republican Senators who indicated their intention to vote against ratification of the Treaty if it came to a vote. Since at least 2/3 of the 100 member Senate (at least 67 Senators) are required to ratify a treaty, consideration of the treaty was deferred again.<ref>{{cite web|last=Johnson|first=Keith|title=GOP Scuttles Law-of-Sea Treaty|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2012/07/16/gop-opposition-scuttles-law-of-sea-treaty/|publisher=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=17 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nSome American commentators, including former Secretary of Defense [[Donald Rumsfeld]], have warned that ratification of the Law of the Sea Treaty might create a precedent with regard to resources of [[outer space]].<ref>Wong, Kristina. [http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2012/jun/14/rumsfeld-hits-law-of-sea-treaty/?page=all \"Rumsfeld still opposes Law of Sea Treaty.\"] ''The Washington Times'', 14 June 2012.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of parties to treaties|United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n[[File:United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea parties.svg|thumb|500px|right|{{legend|#92c5de|Parties}} {{legend|#0571b0|Parties, dually represented by the [[European Union]]}} {{legend|#f4a582|Signatories}} {{legend|#ca0020|Non-parties}}]]\n\nThe [[United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea]] (UNCLOS) is the international agreement that resulted from the third United Nations Conference on the Law of the Sea (UNCLOS III), which took place between 1973 and 1982. The convention was opened for signature on 10 December 1982 and entered into force on 16 November 1994 upon deposition of the 60th instrument of ratification.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/Depts/los/convention_agreements/convention_historical_perspective.htm |title=The United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea (A historical perspective) | publisher=United Nations Division for Ocean Affairs and the Law of the Sea| accessdate=30 April 2009}}</ref> \n\nThe convention has been ratified by 168 parties, which includes 167 states (164 [[United Nations member states]] plus the [[United Nations General Assembly observers|UN Observer state]] [[State of Palestine|Palestine]], as well as the [[Cook Islands]] and [[Niue]]) and the [[European Union]].<ref name=rat/> An additional 14 UN member states have signed, but not ratified the convention.  \n\nSubsequently, the \"Agreement relating to the implementation of Part XI of the United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea\" was signed in 1994, amending the original Convention. The agreement has been ratified by 150 parties (all of which are parties to the Convention), which includes 149 states (146 [[United Nations member states]] plus the [[United Nations General Assembly observers|UN Observer state]] [[State of Palestine|Palestine]], as well as the [[Cook Islands]] and [[Niue]]) and the [[European Union]].<ref name=rat2/> An additional three UN member states have signed, but not ratified the agreement.\n\nAs per Article 4 of the Agreement, following adoption of the Agreement any state which ratifies the convention also becomes a party to the Agreement.  Additionally, only states which are parties to the Convention can ratify the Agreement.\n\n==List of parties==\n\nStates with a dagger ({{dagger}}) are [[landlocked]] states.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!rowspan=2|State<ref name=rat>{{cite web|url=https://treaties.un.org/pages/ViewDetailsIII.aspx?src=TREATY&mtdsg_no=XXI-6&chapter=21&Temp=mtdsg3&clang=_en|title=United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea|accessdate=2013-12-01|publisher=[[United Nations Treaty Series]]}}</ref><ref name=rat2>{{cite web|url=htt